message: ZaniGiovanni, Omnipaedista. These sources who write about Proto-Armenia have long since been deleted by the administration on the Diauehi's page.  You can check, these sources do not lie on the Diauehi#Origins.
The main idea is that Shavsheti is mentioned in the 8th BC.
Hopefully now at least there is no violation. : ))
Sources do not say that Daiuehi was proto-Armenian.
/* Why did you delete the information on the Muski's page? */ new section
/* Source that Colchis was a satrapy */ new section

Sorry, but you did not show me the research where it says that Colchis was the 18th satrapy.  Nowhere in any study is it written that it was a satrap.  In the studies you present, Colchis was under the influence of the Achaemenids and was not a province/Satrapy.  My research isn't old (I mean David Brown, who also mentions Gocha Tsetskhladze's research you are talking about). P.S.  You can add this information to any other location if this location is not available.

Since the map does not fall apart due to a small error and no source writes that Colchis was in the 18th satrapy or any of the satrapies at all.  That's why I'm adding information because people were not misled by the wrong map.
/* Colchis in the 18th Satrapy */ new section

"By the beginning of the fifth century Colchis had come within the  sphere of the Persian empire, which was bounded by the mountains  of the Great Caucasus to its north. However, it seems never to have  been part of a province of that empire. Rather, down to Herodotus'  day at least, it remained a peripheral ally, outside Persia's twenty provinces" - Georgian in antiqueity, David Braund, p.122.              If you return the map, I would like to have a discussion in Talk.
/* Abouth Gorjestan Vilayat and Province */ new section
What stubbornness is this?  His name was David, a Georgian was also a Christian (he later became a Muslim), do you think his name was Davud? It was an extra name by Iran.

This is not my personal opinion.  I request an authoritative source to add when Iran referred to the kingdoms of Eastern Georgia as the "Gorjestan Vilayet", as well as a source to add when the kingdoms of Kartli and Kakheti were a province of Iran that had its own kings.

David XI was Chirstian, His official name was David.  DavuD Khan was an extra name given to the kings of Kartli and Kakheti by the Iranian Empire. For example Heraclius II who was always a Christian and he had the nickname Erekli Khan by Iran.
Gorjestan vilayet was called the Ottoman-occupied territories and not Iran.

1. The Ottoman Empire referred to the territories of Georgia that it had conquered as Georgia (Samtskhe and Kartli (for a short time)). 2. I don't know who are Matthee, Floor & Clawson, but in the sources here it is written in one place that Georgia was a province, then it is referred to as a vassal.  These are two different terms.  Either this source (historians) is mistaken or those present here give a different interpretation to the information written by these authors.
Nimordid and Pharnavazid dynasties are one and the same.
Okay, I will not change the date, but it should be added and did not delete.
Why did you delete it?  This is necessary for all Iberian kings because people will know who the previous and next kings were.  Many find it difficult to find this information on Wikipedia.

Foreign names have always been common among the Kartvelian people: Greek, Persian, Hebrew, Abkhazian - for example Lasha(means "light").... This was the case in all Georgian kingdoms: Georgia, Iberia, Abkhazia, Kartli, Kakheti, etc. Even today Greco-Roman, Hebrew, Persian, Abkhazian etc. names are common among Georgians.
What does this information have to do with Diaokhi?  Whoever added this information, justify the connection with Diaokhi.

Deleted again.  Violation of Wikipedia rules, can not be presented only one opinion, when there are two widely held opinions on the subject.  Please review Wikipedia's rules regarding "Neutral point of view".
Incorrect information was added from the source.
Khutunia Shervashidze was the ruler of Samurzakano(Eastern Abkhazia).
Sorry, but on what basis is it a good source?  There is no non-Armenian source for this version, this version is obviously subjective and does not correspond to the Wikipedia rules.

According to Wikipedia rules, "All encyclopedic content on Wikipedia must be written from a neutral point of view (NPOV)".The author of both sources is Armenian, so this source can not be neitral point of view.

Yes, you are right, and the author writes that information about Iraq, Syria is a historical fiction on the following page (page 251).  But the pages I have written do not contain historical fiction, nor does the author write that it is a fiction.

Ah ok, then it generally refers to the client state.  Ronald Grigor Suny writes in Client State in one episode. Just wrote Roman Republic, Empire, etc.  This makes the reader think that Iberia was conquered at that time, which would mislead everyone.
